text.tspan: A - Agribusiness feeds cities and does so with incredible
efficiency. That industry is moving toward larger and more
autonomous machines.
B - The vast majority of people prefer to live in cities.
Densification, often along commuter rail lines, allows city
populations to increase without encroaching on farmland.
C - Both agribusiness and cities are, however, large net
emitters of CO2. As the climate warms some farmland and
forests may be put at risk or lost to desertification, fires, and
erosion.
Feedback loops from damaged soil can accelerate future land
loss, it can worsen city heat islanding effects, and it can
diminish a population's water supplies.
D - Small carbon-negative agro-forestry households on land-
at-risk have the potential to halt that degradation, restore
habitat, and sink carbon. These homes could be added as
needed to balance city and agribusiness emissions.
The Hundred-Year-Farm project is adapting technology that
could make such households economically feasible someday.
